<p><em>This is my sixteenth post of Scientific Discovery, a newsletter where I’ll share great new scientific research that you may have missed. Check out the <a href="https://salonium.substack.com/about" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">About page</a> if you’re interested in why I’m writing this.</em></p><p>Hello! It’s been almost six months since I’ve done a round up of great research I’ve read, so this post is long &amp; won’t fit on email – but it still only covers a fraction of the things I wanted to share. I hope you enjoy it! If you spot any errors, let me know so I can fix them.</p><p><a href="https://www.scientificdiscovery.dev/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><p>Recently I’ve been thinking about charts that have helped me see something in a new light, and that illustrate an important concept. Here’s one of them.</p><h4>The contours of death</h4><p>Okay, I just enjoy giving spooky titles to my subheadings, but this chart’s very interesting. </p><p>It shows death rates in the US across two dimensions: time and age.</p><p>Splodges show when death rates have risen. You can see how they’ve risen and fallen over time (on the x-axis) and across age groups (on the y-axis). The shades represent death rates. The contour lines around them are like an elevation map: they show how much death rates have risen (or fallen).<a id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1">1</a></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F4cc8fa89-ead3-44f3-8a90-bceabf1e4303_1056x1244.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/3lesoNTH_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/QA0s5h45f_-C_UC-UyKvmt9lN5Jwjv641_A2mH_GNxI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGNjOGZhODktZWFkMy00NGYzLThhOTAtYmNlYWJmMWU0MzAzXzEwNTZ4MTI0NC5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="606" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/F8b-1lXjeAXb3z6gg1oZ1ENrr1b56dno429FfpmU-mE=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY0Y2M4ZmE4OS1lYWQzLTQ0ZjMtOGE5MC1iY2VhYmYxZTQzMDNfMTA1NngxMjQ0LnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/M5vksivCTbDZ4R-RjnZGrmrx7zpl_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/EQgcbqhUQTM-aco7h_tm72k2EN0sk_U9EpX_Oo5kxYo=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNGNjOGZhODktZWFkMy00NGYzLThhOTAtYmNlYWJmMWU0MzAzXzEwNTZ4MTI0NC5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>How have death rates from different causes changed over time and by age (y-axis)?</strong> This is shown as the annual number of deaths per 100,000 people in each age group. The diagonal lines represent birth cohorts – people age along the diagonals. This format is called a <strong>Lexis plot</strong>. Source: <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s13524-018-0680-9" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">A cause-of-death decomposition of young adult excess mortality (Adrien Remund, Carlo G. Camarda and Tim Riffe, 2018)</a></figcaption></figure><p>You’ll see that events with wider splodges occurred over longer time periods. Events with taller splodges affected many age groups. </p><ul><li><p>For example, look at ‘<strong>poisonings</strong>’, which includes substance use and overdoses. Here, it shows the opioid crisis, and you can see it rising gradually across adult age groups. </p></li><li><p>Or look at the <strong>HIV/AIDS</strong> panel: as an exponentially-growing epidemic, it surged over a very short period of time, especially among young and middle-aged adults. </p></li><li><p>Or look at <strong>traffic accidents</strong>, which were especially deadly among young people and the elderly, but have become less so over time.</p></li></ul><p>Suddenly, the plots I’m used to seeing – line charts where something rises for some age groups – seem quite flat, even when they show the same data. </p><p>The shapes show how events permeate<em> </em>across a population and time. I think they also give visual clues about the nature of the underlying events: Were they constrained to only affecting a particular age group? Did they grow exponentially over time? And maybe these tell us something about how and why they happened.</p><p>I really liked this chart, and could look at it for a long time. Are there other types of charts that have helped you understand some data better?</p><p>Here are some little dives into other great research I’ve read!</p><h4>The twin baby boom</h4><p>This new database, called the <a href="https://myshinyapps-hmbd.shinyapps.io/App1/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Human Multiple Births Database</a>, shows national data on twin births from 24 countries. In the chart below you can see trends in having twins, measured as a rate per 1,000 deliveries.</p><p><strong>Twin rates rose from the 1970s across many countries. You can see that they approximately doubled in some countries, from around 10 twins per 1,000 deliveries to 20 or more.</strong></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F86750fad-da18-4082-b06f-0f3e3e623524_1990x1086.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/65-scCIPnJusfoZc- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/atiLGvGbMPmfn5blLPvDSHB9_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7aZJOZn8dKq8ga3VDjPgrUF0TdLUxVK2fvNLg-SotDc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGODY3NTBmYWQtZGExOC00MDgyLWIwNmYtMGYzZTNlNjIzNTI0XzE5OTB4MTA4Ni5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WmrB3h8qdR-p9tOfGn0HFIliRLJfydCgQ_tY8GF2SR8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGODY3NTBmYWQtZGExOC00MDgyLWIwNmYtMGYzZTNlNjIzNTI0XzE5OTB4MTA4Ni5wbmc=" width="728" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/p-f38hEyHxSRXBxeEUau03LlEyfbcddlv0OdP-Ib-es=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY4Njc1MGZhZC1kYTE4LTQwODItYjA2Zi0wZjNlM2U2MjM1MjRfMTk5MHgxMDg2LnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WmrB3h8qdR-p9tOfGn0HFIliRLJfydCgQ_tY8GF2SR8=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGODY3NTBmYWQtZGExOC00MDgyLWIwNmYtMGYzZTNlNjIzNTI0XzE5OTB4MTA4Ni5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>Trends in having twins</strong>, measured as the rate of twins per 1,000 deliveries. Note that the chart shows the <em>fraction of deliveries</em> that were twins. It doesn’t show the birth rate. Source: <a href="https://www.demographic-research.org/volumes/vol48/4/48-4.pdf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The Human Multiple Births Database (HMBD): An international database on twin and other multiple births (Catalina Torres, Arianna Caporali, Gilles Pison, 2023)</a>.</figcaption></figure><p>The main reason for the rise is because women have been having children later on average and using reproductive technologies that were invented then. This includes IVF (where multiple eggs are implanted) and ovarian stimulation (where multiple eggs are released) to make sure that at least one is successful. These can result in having fraternal twins.</p><p><strong>But since the early 2000s, twin rates have plateaued and fallen.</strong> This has happened in a range of countries, as they introduced new standards for reproductive technologies. (Many now measure the success of these technologies by their effect on singleton<a id="footnote-anchor-2" href="#footnote-2">2</a> live births, because pregnancies with multiple babies tend to be riskier.)</p><p>I’d learnt about this at school, but seeing the trend helped me understand the magnitude of twin trends in the population. You can also explore the data for other countries on this <a href="https://myshinyapps-hmbd.shinyapps.io/App1/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">interactive website</a> by the researchers.</p><p><a href="https://www.scientificdiscovery.dev/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><h4>What makes a good conversationalist?</h4><p>Surprisingly, the pandemic provided an opportunity to study this question in detail.</p><p>Volunteers in <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3197" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">this new study</a> had unscripted freeform conversations with strangers over Zoom in 2020, in the United States. They were asked to ‘talk about whatever you like, just imagine you have met someone at a social event and you’re getting to know each other.’</p><p>The conversations were video recorded, and analyzed for patterns of speech and behavior. Then, this was tested against people’s feelings before and after the conversation, and how they rated their conversational partner. In total, the dataset had 1,656 conversations each lasting at least 25 minutes.</p><p>Since the dataset was large and detailed, it could answer a lot of questions. First, <strong>how long are the gaps between each person speaking? Answer: Less than a second on average</strong>, which suggests that people predict when people’s sentences are going to end and how they’ll respond. Some people spoke too soon and their speech slightly overlapped or they interrupted the other person.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6f808520-aabd-4159-9a0f-65fa0ce62f17_1322x1068.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/m7aDslSyF5fyOyzW5M0s_azjzjtXgZF2H6ItCuO-8RA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY2ZjgwODUyMC1hYWJkLTQxNTktOWEwZi02NWZhMGNlNjJmMTdfMTMyMngxMDY4LnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/P7Lhahh8hfNa- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/P6zi2LAbwkTbYU7yq0d67_aeVizgzM_gzyyGEPvCi0Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNmY4MDg1MjAtYWFiZC00MTU5LTlhMGYtNjVmYTBjZTYyZjE3XzEzMjJ4MTA2OC5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1rr4RSaD26Xu8JbIoIP_hu1IN-V2iwWj9yHoe7_ohyM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNmY4MDg1MjAtYWFiZC00MTU5LTlhMGYtNjVmYTBjZTYyZjE3XzEzMjJ4MTA2OC5wbmc=" width="396" alt="" title="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Kjqf3pWEfKYr1- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Vb9ZKvAK_fPkH_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/HIfzCLSkF- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1rr4RSaD26Xu8JbIoIP_hu1IN-V2iwWj9yHoe7_ohyM=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNmY4MDg1MjAtYWFiZC00MTU5LTlhMGYtNjVmYTBjZTYyZjE3XzEzMjJ4MTA2OC5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>The length of a gap between each person speaking, or the length of the overlap between each person speaking. Source: <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3197" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The CANDOR corpus: Insights from a large multimodal dataset of naturalistic conversation. (Andrew Reece, Gus Cooney, Peter Bull, Christine Chung, Bryn Dawson, Casey Fitzpatrick, Tamara Glazer, Dean Knox, Alex Liebscher, Sebastian Marin, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p>What are the most common ‘backchannel words’? These are words people use to show they’re following the other person’s speech. Answer: Yeah and mhm. (This study was done in the US, and it’s likely these vary in other countries.)</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F12c6fc97-b8fd-44e1-8e44-a7dc806a1917_1278x1062.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WaTTYppcw29O4YKUhSZsiQSXPoxsJxrBUdv6X-hwDwk=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYxMmM2ZmM5Ny1iOGZkLTQ0ZTEtOGU0NC1hN2RjODA2YTE5MTdfMTI3OHgxMDYyLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/oAKHYSJnzNaGNRFKB- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7QnLWYwtzG2wUU15DEgGJk_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/nkUnQexrDPrGpJi0vAQpPt51zzj2UIA_Q7-rLG4YCXU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTJjNmZjOTctYjhmZC00NGUxLThlNDQtYTdkYzgwNmExOTE3XzEyNzh4MTA2Mi5wbmc=" width="480" alt="" title="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_GnbeNzTgAhFJwkIibJpQARnBOwEgC0mQL2NGn6F2_I=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYxMmM2ZmM5Ny1iOGZkLTQ0ZTEtOGU0NC1hN2RjODA2YTE5MTdfMTI3OHgxMDYyLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/WLTErpwUTUV4l3tRDQCFfI_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/nkUnQexrDPrGpJi0vAQpPt51zzj2UIA_Q7-rLG4YCXU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMTJjNmZjOTctYjhmZC00NGUxLThlNDQtYTdkYzgwNmExOTE3XzEyNzh4MTA2Mi5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>The most common ‘backchannel words’</strong>, which are words people use to show they’re following the other person’s speech. Source: <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3197" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The CANDOR corpus: Insights from a large multimodal dataset of naturalistic conversation. (Andrew Reece, Gus Cooney, Peter Bull, Christine Chung, Bryn Dawson, Casey Fitzpatrick, Tamara Glazer, Dean Knox, Alex Liebscher, Sebastian Marin, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p><strong>Were people happier after a freeform conversation with a stranger? Yes, on average!</strong> You can see this across age groups below. Volunteers were asked to rate their happiness on a 9-point scale immediately before and after the conversation.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F0dff7e4e-82c6-4ab0-96c6-b26c6b3ee3cc_1420x1432.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/4WsBmMXJr4rBW8e6oZPIbn8Bk2fnDHHmSxG6iuTpB_Q=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYwZGZmN2U0ZS04MmM2LTRhYjAtOTZjNi1iMjZjNmIzZWUzY2NfMTQyMHgxNDMyLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_z2KE3QJwJ--28ny5QZzLj- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/GCFJPiylboxKmojQpgOy6Nwg- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XAlJ2pPKJT8Klg_" width="562" alt="" title="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/ZULH3Rwkbr95JKQRNP-8CZFCMcbEQ_qJVAeeB562kbY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYwZGZmN2U0ZS04MmM2LTRhYjAtOTZjNi1iMjZjNmIzZWUzY2NfMTQyMHgxNDMyLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/02kjReNfaphBlf9eCEy4PUv41YclnYyJIVNYgsjJw-E=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkYwZGZmN2U0ZS04MmM2LTRhYjAtOTZjNi1iMjZjNmIzZWUzY2NfMTQyMHgxNDMyLnBuZw== 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/G70OxrFr7Bwyura- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/XAlJ2pPKJT8Klg_ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>How positive did people feel before and after a conversation? </strong>Volunteers were asked to rate their happiness on a 9-point scale immediately before and after the conversation. This is a density plot: the peaks show where most people’s responses were. Source: <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3197" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The CANDOR corpus: Insights from a large multimodal dataset of naturalistic conversation. (Andrew Reece, Gus Cooney, Peter Bull, Christine Chung, Bryn Dawson, Casey Fitzpatrick, Tamara Glazer, Dean Knox, Alex Liebscher, Sebastian Marin, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p>Although I wonder how much this came from the sample – people who like having conversations were probably more likely to join the study, and it happened during the pandemic, when many people were probably very bored at home.</p><p>Finally, <strong>what makes a good conversationalist?</strong></p><p>Volunteers were asked: ‘Imagine you were to rank the last 100 people you had a conversation with according to how good of a conversationalist they are. ‘0’ is the least good conversationalist you’ve talked to. ‘50’ is right in the middle. ‘100’ is the best conversationalist. Where would you rank the person that you just talked to on this scale?’</p><p><strong>People who were rated higher by their conversational partners tended to speak fairly quickly, and with more emotional intensity. Also, they tended to use more head movement (nodding for yes and shaking for no) while listening, and showed more facial signs of happiness.</strong><a id="footnote-anchor-3" href="#footnote-3">3</a></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F1a4f7a9f-4f35-4f5c-9c92-6546fdbc9428_1370x1326.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/VaY7G_Uy-3KqukxzJAL_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_PUnS1uV6lotI_cfraycN461J9WNs-Wxogys-83AZAQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMWE0ZjdhOWYtNGYzNS00ZjVjLTljOTItNjU0NmZkYmM5NDI4XzEzNzB4MTMyNi5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7wGdmBuoxmZxHkmxSxAE2oE-bQSifSsrXGY1pnFz-3o=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMWE0ZjdhOWYtNGYzNS00ZjVjLTljOTItNjU0NmZkYmM5NDI4XzEzNzB4MTMyNi5wbmc=" width="542" alt="" title="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/zs9ARkw_4_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/7wGdmBuoxmZxHkmxSxAE2oE-bQSifSsrXGY1pnFz-3o=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGMWE0ZjdhOWYtNGYzNS00ZjVjLTljOTItNjU0NmZkYmM5NDI4XzEzNzB4MTMyNi5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>What makes a good conversationalist?</strong> Volunteers were asked to rate their conversation partner. The blue points show the top-rated conversationalists. The red points show the bottom-rated conversationalists. The x-axis shows how they behaved across a given measure (e.g. speaking slowly – quickly). The y-axis shows the proportion of ‘turns’ in their conversation where they behaved that way (e.g. 10% of their turns were spoken quickly). Source: <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.adf3197" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">The CANDOR corpus: Insights from a large multimodal dataset of naturalistic conversation. (Andrew Reece, Gus Cooney, Peter Bull, Christine Chung, Bryn Dawson, Casey Fitzpatrick, Tamara Glazer, Dean Knox, Alex Liebscher, Sebastian Marin, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p>I really liked this paper because it described many basic aspects of conversations, and compared the analysis across different pattern-recognition software.</p><p><a href="https://www.scientificdiscovery.dev/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><p>Here’s something else cool.</p><h4>Are speakers of tonal languages better at discerning music?</h4><p>You might know that I grew up in Hong Kong, where most people speak Cantonese. </p><p>It’s considered a difficult language to learn to speak because it’s a ‘tonal language’ – each syllable can be spoken in 6 different tones.<a id="footnote-anchor-4" href="#footnote-4">4</a> This means the pitch of a syllable can be either rising, falling, stable, or falling-then-rising; and can start at different levels. </p><p>The tone provides information about the word: if you say a word with the wrong tone, people might think you’ve said a completely different word. Here’s an example:</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb0f4e77f-771f-484c-87fc-51f3308bf8da_1156x1190.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/pkj8qkGNmas5hcwp_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/1qH-uNDqjQ-qIbCWZhdjtLEFoPukvc4x9QLQ2x--YnQ=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGYjBmNGU3N2YtNzcxZi00ODRjLTg3ZmMtNTFmMzMwOGJmOGRhXzExNTZ4MTE5MC5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/FCxuR9KI1HJcPxWRRk27FOhdJBVC9_t0cIcaAwbRJKI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGYjBmNGU3N2YtNzcxZi00ODRjLTg3ZmMtNTFmMzMwOGJmOGRhXzExNTZ4MTE5MC5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux." width="252" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/p3kX1rSdqUpOaJSzCdjFECXdRJJic_yYrtNMr2BSm_Y=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZiMGY0ZTc3Zi03NzFmLTQ4NGMtODdmYy01MWYzMzA4YmY4ZGFfMTE1NngxMTkwLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/dGY6NQst4fTu-bgxtS9WUUQ5Wp_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>Tones in Cantonese.</strong> When the syllable ‘si’ is spoken with different pitch changes, it corresponds to different words. Diagram from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantonese_phonology" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Wikipedia</a>.</figcaption></figure><p>I listen to Cantopop and Vietpop music sometimes<a id="footnote-anchor-5" href="#footnote-5">5</a>, and I’ve occasionally wondered about the relationship between music and tones: Do they constrain the compositions that songwriters can make? Are tonal speakers better at matching a pitch?</p><p><a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(23)00387-1" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">A new study</a> looks at this topic. <strong>The researchers created a music game (<a href="https://www.themusiclab.org/quizzes/miq" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">here’s the link</a>) to test if people could notice slight changes in melody, tuning, and beats.</strong> It was played by 493,100 participants around the world, who spoke 54 different languages in total.</p><p>They found that <strong>people who spoke tonal languages – like Mandarin, Cantonese and Vietnamese – generally tended to do better at distinguishing melodies, but weren’t as good as others at perceiving beats. </strong>You can see this below.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F7241abc0-bd52-4e4b-95de-df6a7366b529_1886x1414.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/QS_x3wMdwuKc0k66V_NbLvws- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_90PGPemrMTKD8HlzC0CsBfvu53BYDFQUsvB2_ow_cI=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY3MjQxYWJjMC1iZDUyLTRlNGItOTVkZS1kZjZhNzM2NmI1MjlfMTg4NngxNDE0LnBuZw== 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/PjkjMIS9lcNuPb6afVxzcZ-WvdddV-tUVDWHnJUjD-A=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNzI0MWFiYzAtYmQ1Mi00ZTRiLTk1ZGUtZGY2YTczNjZiNTI5XzE4ODZ4MTQxNC5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/W9X-wc8VAtuxqnqpaoRndW_FzHuZW_zCnA5ltq6Wiu4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNzI0MWFiYzAtYmQ1Mi00ZTRiLTk1ZGUtZGY2YTczNjZiNTI5XzE4ODZ4MTQxNC5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mpeDB_SVODE-Wr_aieBfe-__" width="728" height="546" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/YLFs-Cfa4SG4FCRdWO_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/HCMj- 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tlQn3K1AAwboiOPqlG3WTMvjLWAIAsuxFSDDeZ-gSDY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGNzI0MWFiYzAtYmQ1Mi00ZTRiLTk1ZGUtZGY2YTczNjZiNTI5XzE4ODZ4MTQxNC5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/mpeDB_SVODE-Wr_aieBfe-__ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>How speakers of different languages performed at distinguishing slight differences in melody, tuning or beats.</strong> This chart shows their performance relative to the average speaker of a non-tonal language, such as English. This is adjusted for their age, gender, and whether they’ve taken music lessons. The dots show point estimates and the error bars show 95% confidence intervals. Numbers in brackets show the number of participants who spoke each language. Source: <a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(23)00387-1" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Language experience predicts music processing in a half-million speakers of fifty-four languages (Jingxuan Liu, Courtney B. Hilton, Elika Bergelson, Samuel A. Mehr, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p>The authors suggest maybe this is because they place more weight on cues that are relevant to their language.</p><p>When I read studies like this, I try to imagine the different kinds of people who might be participants – could they vary on skills relevant to the game? Could their skills vary between countries or languages, for other reasons?</p><p>Here the study was an online game. So I’m thinking: maybe people from some cultures are more likely to play musical instruments, or the game got shared on music forums in some countries. Also, maybe people speaking some languages understood the game instructions better, or were more familiar with the melodies or rhythms in the game.</p><p>This study adjusted and explored several of those factors. You can see below that <strong>people who have taken music lessons performed better on all three parts of the game, across language types.</strong></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F90b253e7-d762-4f9b-a4cd-613d99ab2071_1642x654.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/5tVD6G99pMtbHudsbixjpRkA8yN4YgV_U6gjAU38BoA=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY5MGIyNTNlNy1kNzYyLTRmOWItYTRjZC02MTNkOTlhYjIwNzFfMTY0Mng2NTQucG5n 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/cPl9sfCFfv_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/niJ6JNiAeaUpQ-ZQ- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tJxND_0JwjTYO6bgwbww-" width="604" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/VXgfSjf2dJ9qwuw_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/9lV9LX9vc_bq2DLZ_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/tJxND_0JwjTYO6bgwbww- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>How people who have taken music lessons (or haven’t) performed on three tests of music perception.</strong> This is split by the type of language they speak. It shows their performance relative to the average speaker of a non-tonal language, such as English. The dots show point estimates and the error bars show 95% confidence intervals. Source: <a href="https://www.cell.com/current-biology/fulltext/S0960-9822(23)00387-1" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Language experience predicts music processing in a half-million speakers of fifty-four languages (Jingxuan Liu, Courtney B. Hilton, Elika Bergelson, Samuel A. Mehr, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><p>The researchers say that “in each case, <strong>the effect size associated with being a tonal language speaker was roughly half as large as the effect of receiving music lessons</strong>, indicating an effect of substantive practical significance.” </p><p>I think that’s a good way to put the advantage into context! It’s also cool to use a large online game in research, to get enough people from different backgrounds, and where you can fine-tune parts of the experiment.</p><p><a href="https://www.scientificdiscovery.dev/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><h4>Do blood pressure drugs’ effects vary between people?</h4><p>When we try to understand whether something works, it’s actually challenging to tell if it works for everyone somewhat <em><strong>or</strong></em> if it works for some people but not others.</p><p>The main reason for this is that we’re only able to see one version of history: When someone makes a decision, we can see what follows, but we can’t see what would’ve happened if they had made a different decision.</p><p>Even in a randomized controlled trial, each person is allocated to only one of the groups<em> </em>at a time. So we don’t get to see whether they, specifically, would have gotten better anyway. We only get to see the change for people <strong>on average</strong>.<a id="footnote-anchor-6" href="#footnote-6">6</a></p><p>This distinction – between averages and individuals – is also blurry when people naturally experience a lot of fluctuations. For example, there’s a lot of day-to-day variation in people’s blood pressure – so maybe for some of them, it was just a good day, and for others it was a bad day.</p><p>But there are ways to get closer to an answer. One way is by understanding the mechanism of each drug – for example, many cancer patients get genetic testing on their tumours, and then receive treatment for their specific cancer mutations. Another way is by testing the effect in different subgroups, although you might need very large sample sizes to find the precise differences between them. </p><p>A third way is to track people’s fluctuations while theyʼre using the same drug or not, and adjust for this. This helps to see the probability that people would do better anyway, without the drug.</p><p>That’s what <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2803518" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">this new RCT</a> did. 280 patients with hypertension were randomly allocated to <strong>each of four different drugs (one after the other), and then two of the same drugs again</strong>. Their blood pressure was measured 14 times a day. The drugs were lisinopril, candesartan, hydrochlorothiazide and amlodipine; each comes from a different drug class.</p><p>Let’s see the results! (This chart looks complicated but I’ll explain it below.)</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff09a87d6-b32f-417a-97f8-d385f0329770_1920x1208.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Q4pLaPKsRH5v2vAp0QLHu- 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wXKKR- 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/DdKEYLrweeP_Ng_dXG_" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/jir5hTvNT3o-P4h06LBNGec_CloYV-PXkR_J7QhLUvw=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZmMDlhODdkNi1iMzJmLTQxN2EtOTdmOC1kMzg1ZjAzMjk3NzBfMTkyMHgxMjA4LnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/M11ZtvkFfoiaBbfyYvuw1wPka-K_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/DdKEYLrweeP_Ng_dXG_ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>A comparison between people’s systolic blood pressure (SBP, measured in mmHg) on different anti-hypertensive drugs. Each dot represents one participant. The axes show the average systolic blood pressure in participants who took one drug, compared with their average systolic blood pressure on another drug. Source: <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2803518" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Heterogeneity in blood pressure response to 4 antihypertensive drugs: A randomized controlled trial. (Johan Sundström, Lars Lind, Shamim Nowrouzi, et al., 2023)</a></figcaption></figure><ul><li><p>Each dot represents a participant. You’ll see that some dots have a range – that tells you the participant was given the same drug twice, and it shows the variation in their blood pressure over the repeated drug. <strong>You can see that there’s often a lot of variation within the same people.</strong></p></li><li><p>The blue diagonal line shows a comparison between people’s blood pressure on one drug to it on another drug. The black diagonal line shows where it would be if there was no difference between the drugs. You can see that for some pairs of drugs, the two lines are more apart, and there are differences in drug efficacy.<strong> For example, patients taking hydrochlorothiazide have a 5.1 mmHg higher blood pressure than those taking amlodipine, on average. Lisinopril was the most effective, on average.</strong></p></li><li><p>Because of the design of the trial, the researchers could also test whether different people did better on some drugs than others. With this, they estimated that <strong>if the participants received personalized treatment with a single drug that worked better for them, they’d have a 4.4 mmHg lower blood pressure on average.</strong> They also estimated that personalized treatment would be better than if all of them received the most effective drug (lisinopril).</p></li></ul><p><a href="https://www.scientificdiscovery.dev/subscribe?" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Subscribe now</a></p><h4>Even more</h4><p>Here’s a more condensed summary of some other great stuff I’ve read.</p><ul><li><p>Can we save Tasmanian devils from contagious cancers?</p><ul><li><p>Something you may not have heard of. The population of Tasmanian devils has dropped by around two-thirds in the last 25 years. They’ve been affected by facial cancers, which spread when they bite each other during fights.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F81807d55-c9f4-4782-9261-c87ca174c673_2128x1084.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/xfhUUYT-_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/uhJZaJ4_ 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/iVyFzm-" width="598" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/l1l8-hqxBj_ 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/iVyFzm- 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>The declining population and density of Tasmanian devils, and the rise of the Devil Facial Tumour</strong> (DFT1 &amp; 2). The spread of the cancers may now be slowing down because of lower population density of the devils, and some adaptation, but they’re still vulnerable. Source: <a href="https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/ele.13703" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Quantifying 25 years of disease-caused declines in Tasmanian devil populations: host density drives spatial pathogen spread (Calum X. Cunningham et al., 2021)</a></figcaption></figure></li><li><p>There are two types of these cancers, called Devil Facial Tumour 1 and 2. They each cause very similar disease, but <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.abq6453" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">a recent study</a> shows that each type evolved independently. (This <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-47659640" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">BBC article</a> has more background and photos in case you’re interested.)</p></li><li><p>Now, <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-023-02124-4" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">field trials</a> are about to begin to test vaccines that could protect them. </p></li><li><p>They’ll be rolled out as oral bait, similar to how oral rabies vaccines have been given to <a href="https://rr-europe.woah.org/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/florence_cliquet_wrd2021.pdf" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">wildlife across Europe</a> (which happened by dropping them from helicopters and aircraft). I hope the devil cancer vaccines succeed!</p></li></ul></li><li><p>A new study shows how estimates of people’s beliefs in conspiracy theories are often overestimated (<a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/political-analysis/article/acquiescence-bias-inflates-estimates-of-conspiratorial-beliefs-and-political-misperceptions/36461392CC22A6AC6813767D64490A64" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Seth J. Hill and Margaret E. Roberts, 2023</a>).</p><ul><li><p>Estimates are usually based on surveys where people are asked whether they agree or disagree with a conspiratorial belief. <strong>Unfortunately people tend to prefer to agree across surveys, which is called ‘acquiescence bias’. </strong>This leads to overestimating how many people actually believe something.</p></li><li><p>The researchers show this by asking the same questions in multiple different styles, like randomly flipping the phrasing of the question so the agree/disagree responses would be flipped.</p></li><li><p>I also liked this quote from the study: “The consequences of bias increase in the rarity of the target belief. <strong>The smaller the fraction of the population that holds a belief—e.g., when asking about outlandish conspiracies—the more likely agreeable responses are due to acquiescence bias rather than actual belief.</strong>”</p></li></ul></li><li><p>You might have heard of ‘<strong>left-digit bias</strong>.’ This is the idea that customers tend to treat prices like $3.99 as being much lower than $4.00.</p><ul><li><p>Here’s an example from a recent paper (<a href="https://academic.oup.com/restud/advance-article-abstract/doi/10.1093/restud/rdac082/6931812" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Strulov-Shlain, 2022</a>). The author looks at how the demand for products changes as the price rises, by using data on price changes and sales of the same products over time, from around 3,600 stores in the US.  </p></li><li><p>You can see this below. There are sudden drops in demand as prices reach a new digit. <strong>The author estimates that customers treat a 1 cent rise at the boundary (from $3.99 to $4.00, for example) as a 20 cent rise.</strong></p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe86efffc-f8d8-4fe7-b2db-68fed83a94e1_1680x1222.png" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux. 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/QpdiRq5Gf4xlOo2m2t4XXn46rMBSPUmonAv2b_4PFtY=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTg2ZWZmZmMtZjhkOC00ZmU3LWIyZGItNjhmZWQ4M2E5NGUxXzE2ODB4MTIyMi5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RjGZewzzLMvJ2tMetNtnuK3uem561hRHP_RuZelqvk4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTg2ZWZmZmMtZjhkOC00ZmU3LWIyZGItNjhmZWQ4M2E5NGUxXzE2ODB4MTIyMi5wbmc=" width="600" alt="" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/xWkdkC4IfB6QAUbKVX_ArsmUifn3ZE_vuRr81bgGsqg=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZlODZlZmZmYy1mOGQ4LTRmZTctYjJkYi02OGZlZDgzYTk0ZTFfMTY4MHgxMjIyLnBuZw== 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/wZuYACvENmd5MXQpae1CWfYc_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/rP9O3KHIAGjOGWfVHFUhDMYGcGssQ_venxrfPk_ZZDg=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTg2ZWZmZmMtZjhkOC00ZmU3LWIyZGItNjhmZWQ4M2E5NGUxXzE2ODB4MTIyMi5wbmc= 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/RjGZewzzLMvJ2tMetNtnuK3uem561hRHP_RuZelqvk4=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGZTg2ZWZmZmMtZjhkOC00ZmU3LWIyZGItNjhmZWQ4M2E5NGUxXzE2ODB4MTIyMi5wbmc= 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption><strong>Left-digit bias</strong> in customers’ perception of prices. Source: <a href="https://academic.oup.com/restud/advance-article-abstract/doi/10.1093/restud/rdac082/6931812" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">More than a penny’s worth: Left-digit bias and firm pricing (Avner Strulov-Shlain, 2023)</a></figcaption></figure></li></ul></li><li><p><strong>Did the 1918 flu pandemic cause a baby boom two years later, in 1920 Europe?</strong></p><ul><li><p>According to <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/3654904" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">a 2004 study</a> using data from Norway, the end of the 1918 Spanish flu pandemic led to a baby boom.</p></li><li><p><a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00324728.2023.2192041" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">A new study</a> challenges this view, and argues that it was actually the end of WWI (or rather the post-WWI economy) that led to the baby boom. </p></li><li><p>The authors look at more neutral countries, not just Norway, and show that communities with the biggest baby busts in 1919 <em>also </em>had baby busts in 1920.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fcce02ddb-b441-415b-9c47-fbbd5fc4a458_1500x1029.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/zfl4iClLGz0MCEkNRCpK0p7ngWsfX6wLZcIP_26Hm7A=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd180MjQsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZjY2UwMmRkYi1iNDQxLTQxNWItOWM0Ny1mYmJkNWZjNGE0NThfMTUwMHgxMDI5LmpwZWc= 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/vbmOnNqNbYid1H0wWPtXoL0ys0V8hTl-dvwuIB1xaEc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZjY2UwMmRkYi1iNDQxLTQxNWItOWM0Ny1mYmJkNWZjNGE0NThfMTUwMHgxMDI5LmpwZWc= 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux. 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_" width="456" alt="Image" title="Image" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/TPbFbJ5oUXy3gW_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Py9IhivwhEe5yUzT4Sx1JluM9Uk6avMLav-qKejYmCs=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX2F1dG8scV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkZjY2UwMmRkYi1iNDQxLTQxNWItOWM0Ny1mYmJkNWZjNGE0NThfMTUwMHgxMDI5LmpwZWc= 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/_ 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>Communities that had lower birth rates in 1919 (compared to 1916–1918) also had lower birth rates in 1920. Source: <a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00324728.2023.2192041" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Did the 1918 influenza pandemic cause a 1920 baby boom? Demographic evidence from neutral Europe. (Hampton Gaddy and Mathias Mølbak Ingholt)</a></figcaption></figure></li><li><p>Another important point is that, while the 1918 flu pandemic was a global phenomenon, the 1920 baby boom was largely concentrated in Europe.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F91d50e7e-e64c-4605-af35-177e5e49aa1c_1500x1030.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/Drrud8TPk9DA4SpmIIA8beIckiM_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/2_ 848w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/DbeMOUHLqeJmkp007YO7N5aAFmdh4fXr0_Mj58NWHok=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xMjcyLGNfbGltaXQsZl93ZWJwLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGOTFkNTBlN2UtZTY0Yy00NjA1LWFmMzUtMTc3ZTVlNDlhYTFjXzE1MDB4MTAzMC5qcGVn 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/0HtJ3MF1Hup_ktZFy5vNo3Kv- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/q5DEpzqg3moE0yecb1M4UW0Fplfie-trZzi053pBOuc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGOTFkNTBlN2UtZTY0Yy00NjA1LWFmMzUtMTc3ZTVlNDlhYTFjXzE1MDB4MTAzMC5qcGVn" width="436" alt="Image" title="Image" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/76tBsoo-05c9I6c23DwZb_ 424w, https://reader.miniflux. 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/q5DEpzqg3moE0yecb1M4UW0Fplfie-trZzi053pBOuc=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpnb29kLGZsX3Byb2dyZXNzaXZlOnN0ZWVwL2h0dHBzJTNBJTJGJTJGc3Vic3RhY2stcG9zdC1tZWRpYS5zMy5hbWF6b25hd3MuY29tJTJGcHVibGljJTJGaW1hZ2VzJTJGOTFkNTBlN2UtZTY0Yy00NjA1LWFmMzUtMTc3ZTVlNDlhYTFjXzE1MDB4MTAzMC5qcGVn 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"/></picture></a><figcaption>The crude birth rate (CBR) in countries in 1920, relative to 1915–17. Source: <a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00324728.2023.2192041" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Did the 1918 influenza pandemic cause a 1920 baby boom? Demographic evidence from neutral Europe. (Hampton Gaddy and Mathias Mølbak Ingholt)</a></figcaption></figure></li></ul></li><li><p>Have you heard of ‘<strong>multipartite viruses</strong>’? These are viruses that are made up of different segments that spread <em>separately</em>, but then they have to infect the <em>same cell</em> in order to replicate.</p><ul><li><p>This seems like a huge disadvantage – since most of the time, they won’t all infect the same cell, so most lineages die out. So why have multipartite viruses evolved several times independently? Why don’t they all eventually die out?</p></li><li><p>A <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.3002092" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">new study</a> uses theoretical simulations to argue that they’ve evolved by <strong>cheating</strong>, and that there are more advantages to this than previously thought.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-medi